        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>2. Hesketh Crescent | Torquay</placeName>
                    <date>July 4<hi rend="superscript">th</hi></date>
                    <salute>My dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I must thank you for your extraordinary kindness to me about Corallorhiza.<ref target="#foot.f2"/> M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Watson forwarded to me your note to him<ref target="#foot.f3"/> &amp; he suggested Prof. Balfour to whom I have written.<ref target="#foot.f4"/> I fear that there is no chance of my succeeding; but I am sure I am not the less obliged to you for your great kindness.—</p>
<p>My dear Sir | Yours truly obliged | Charles Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The year is given by reference to the Darwins’ stay in Torquay.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">Gordon had offered to assist CD in acquiring specimens of the orchid <hi rend="italic">Corallorhiza</hi>. See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-3191.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to George Gordon, 22 June [1861]</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">The letter from <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_4975.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Hewett Cottrell Watson</ref> has not been found. Gordon may have written to him after receiving CD’s letter of 17 June [1861].</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_259.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">John Hutton Balfour</ref> was professor of botany at <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1454.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Edinburgh University</ref> and director of the Royal Botanic Garden.</note>
        </div>        
            
